    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE / 9200 9300 9400 MODELS BUILT AFTER JANUARY 1, 1995 - CATERPILLAR
        3176B/3406E ELECTRONIC ENGINE CONTROLS - 1994 - ELECTRICAL OPERATION - SPEEDOMETER/TACHOMETER INPUTS
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="x0814830" svcproctype="IDcomponent" graphiccount="0">
        <title>SPEEDOMETER/TACHOMETER INPUTS</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <para>Refer to
                <emph type="bold">
                    <hotlnk document="s08148_36.xml" xrefid="x0814804">CIRCUIT DIAGRAMS</hotlnk>, Figures
                    <hotlnk document="s08148_7.xml" xrefid="f0814801">6.07</hotlnk>
                    or
                    <hotlnk document="s08148_7.xml" xrefid="f0814802">6.10</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk document="s08148_9.xml" xrefid="f0814807">6.11</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                , for this discussion.
            </para>
            <para>The input signal to the speedometer and tachometer with the 3176B and 3406E Caterpillar engines is
                provided by the ECM through the ATA data link circuits 98(+) and 98B(-) to Datalink Positive bus
                connector (514) and Datalink Negative bus connector (515), then circuit 47/48(+) from (514) and 47/48(-)
                from (515) connect to the speedometer/tachometer unit at connector (595). Also refer to
                <emph type="bold">
                    <hotlnk document="s08148_9.xml" xrefid="x0814816">ATA DATA LINK CONNECTOR (220)</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                for discussion of data link circuits.
            </para>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Speedometer/Tachometer Unit</title>
            <para>Refer to
                <emph type="bold">
                    <hotlnk document="s08148_36.xml" xrefid="x0814804">CIRCUIT DIAGRAMS</hotlnk>, Figure
                    <hotlnk document="s08148_9.xml" xrefid="f0814807">6.11</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                , for this discussion.
            </para>
            <para>The speedometer/tachometer cluster initially used with the 3176B and 3406E engines was International
                part number 1682010C91. Since that time improvements have been made to the unit and the part number was
                revised to 1682010C92, then to 1682010C93. There are some differences in how they were programmed, so
                each will be discussed separately. The part number appears on the back of each cluster, along with the
                initial factory settings.
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Speedometer/Tachometer - 1682010C91</emph>
            </para>
            <para>The speedometer/tachometer has two sets of Dip Switches, ten in each set. One set is for the
                speedometer and one set is for the tachometer.
                <emph type="bold">The ten speedometer dip switches are physically positioned in the one position at the
                    factory.
                </emph>
            </para>
            <para>Speedometer - 1111111111</para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">The tachometer requires the eight switches on the left switch bank to be physically
                    positioned in the one position.
                </emph>
                The ninth switch is not used (set at zero) and the tenth switch is for miles (0 position) or kilometers
                (1 position). A unit set for miles would look like the following:
            </para>
            <para>Tachometer - 1111111100</para>
            <para>These settings program the speedometer/tachometer unit to operate using inputs (serial data
                transmissions) from the ECM over the data link.
                <emph type="bold">If the tire size or rear axle ratios are changed, the ECM programming, not the
                    speedometer unit, has to be changed</emph>.
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Speedometer/Tachometer - 1682010C92 and 1682010C93</emph>
            </para>
            <para>The speedometer/tachometer cluster has two sets of Dip Switches, ten in each set. One set is for the
                speedometer and one set is for the tachometer. For the C92 and C93 part number clusters,
                <emph type="bold">the ten speedometer and the ten tachometer dip switches are physically positioned in
                    the
                </emph>
                <emph type="bold">zero position.</emph>
                They are
                <emph type="underscr">electronically programmed</emph>
                to the following settings:
            </para>
            <para>Speedometer - 1111111111</para>
            <para>Tachometer - 1111111100 (miles/hr)</para>
            <para>1111111101 (kilometers/hr)</para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>ECM Speedometer Programming</title>
            <para>The ECM receives a vehicle speed signal from the International installed vehicle speed sensor or
                Allison installed speed sensor.
                <emph type="italic">The ECM is programmed with the number of pulses per mile from the vehicle speed
                    sensor.
                </emph>
            </para>
            <para>If the vehicle tire size, axle ratio or number of teeth on the transmission speedometer gear are
                changed,
                <emph type="bold">the ECM will have to be reprogrammed with the new pulses per mile data.</emph>
                The speedometer/tachometer unit does not get reprogrammed. The Prolink EST or Caterpillar EST can be
                used for the reprogramming. Refer to Caterpillar or Prolink manual for this procedure.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Calculating Pulses Per Mile (PPM)</title>
            <para>PPM= M x Ra x N</para>
            <para>M = Tire revolutions per mile = 10085 divided by the tire radius. Also the following table
                <hotlnk document="s08148_8.xml" xrefid="t0814803">(Figure 2.05)</hotlnk>
                lists revolutions per mile for various size tires. The table information is an average from several tire
                manufacturers. Tire manufacturers can also provide specific information for their tires.
            </para>
